h3. Issue Summary
* As per the title, whenever a PR is merged using the fast-forward strategy, you get the following error message when trying to revert it:
{code}
Unable to revert pull request

The resulting revert would cause conflicts on one or more files. You will need to resolve these conflicts manually or create a new pull request to revert these changes.
{code}
* On the console log, we get a 400 with the following response:
{code}
{"type": "error", "error": {"message": "The merge commit doesn't have exactly two parent commits."}}
{code}

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a *branchB* from *branchA*;
# Commit your changes to *branchB*;
# Open a pull request from *branchB* to *branchA*;
# Merge it using the fast-forward merging strategy;
# Try to revert the PR;

h3. Expected Results
* The PR should be reverted;

h3. Actual Results
* An error occurs and it is not possible to revert the PR;

h3. Workaround
Even though it is not possible to revert the Pull Request through the Bitbucket UI, it is still possible to do so from the command line:
# Identify the last commit before *branchB* was created with {code}$ git log{code}
#  Grab the commit SHA and run {code}$ git revert <SHA>{code}
# This might generate a few conflicts that will need to be resolved locally;
# Commit the changes and push to the remote;

h3. Issue Summary
* Making a call to the Activity API endpoint, info such as *context_lines, to, path, outdated, from* is not being automatically retrieved for inline comments;

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a Pull Request;
 # Add an inline comment to any file in the diff;
 # Make a GET request to the Activity endpoint for that Pull Request;

h3. Expected Results
* The information from the inline comment should be automatically fetched;

h3. Actual Results
* The inline field is coming enmpty in the response body;

h3. Workaround
* It is possible to workaround this issue by forcing the API to get those specific values:
{code}Curl -X GET -u <username>:<apppassword> "https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/<workspace>/<repo>/pullrequests/<id>/activity?fields=%2Bvalues.comment.inline.*"{code}

The instructions on the page shown when a new repository is created currently includes:

{{git remote add origin <redacted>}}
{{git push -u origin master}}

Here, "master" is no longer the default branch name.  The site should either detect the right default branch name, or use some stylistic way of indicating that the user should edit that part before executing.

Of course, experienced users would not have any trouble knowing what to do, but changing this might help new users.

Cheers.

